Use `cc.eventManager.addListener` with `cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE`:

```typescript
cc.eventManager.addListener({
    event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
    swallowTouches: true,
    onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): boolean => {
        const loc = touch.getLocation();
        cc.log('Touch began at:', loc.x, loc.y);
        return true; // must return true to receive onTouchMoved/onTouchEnded
    },
    onTouchEnded: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): void => {
        cc.log('Touch ended');
    }
}, myNode);
```

The second argument is the node the listener is associated with. Returning `true` from `onTouchBegan` is required to receive subsequent move and end callbacks.

These are two different touch handling modes:

**TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE** — Receives individual touch events. Best for UI elements like buttons. Each callback gets a single `cc.Touch` object. You must return `true` from `onTouchBegan` to claim the touch.

```typescript
cc.eventManager.addListener({
    event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
    swallowTouches: true,
    onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event) => true,
    onTouchMoved: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.EventTouch) => {},
    onTouchEnded: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event) => {}
}, node);
```

**TOUCH_ALL_AT_ONCE** — Receives all active touches in a single callback. Best for multi-touch gestures like pinch-to-zoom. Callbacks receive `cc.Touch[]`.

```typescript
cc.eventManager.addListener({
    event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ALL_AT_ONCE,
    onTouchesBegan: (touches: cc.Touch[], event: cc.Event) => {},
    onTouchesMoved: (touches: cc.Touch[], event: cc.Event) => {},
    onTouchesEnded: (touches: cc.Touch[], event: cc.Event) => {}
}, node);
```

Use ONE_BY_ONE for buttons and draggable items; use ALL_AT_ONCE for multi-finger gestures.

Use `cc.EventListener.KEYBOARD` with `onKeyPressed` and `onKeyReleased` callbacks:

```typescript
cc.eventManager.addListener({
    event: cc.EventListener.KEYBOARD,
    onKeyPressed: (keyCode: cc.KEY, event: cc.Event): void => {
        if (keyCode === cc.KEY.space) {
            cc.log('Space pressed - jump!');
        } else if (keyCode === cc.KEY.left) {
            cc.log('Move left');
        }
    },
    onKeyReleased: (keyCode: cc.KEY, event: cc.Event): void => {
        cc.log('Key released:', keyCode);
    }
}, this);
```

Common key codes include `cc.KEY.space` (32), `cc.KEY.left` (37), `cc.KEY.up` (38), `cc.KEY.right` (39), `cc.KEY.down` (40), `cc.KEY.enter` (13), and `cc.KEY.a` through `cc.KEY.z` (65-90).

Use `cc.EventListener.MOUSE` which provides callbacks for down, up, move, and scroll:

```typescript
cc.eventManager.addListener({
    event: cc.EventListener.MOUSE,
    onMouseDown: (event: cc.EventMouse): void => {
        if (event.getButton() === cc.EventMouse.BUTTON_LEFT) {
            cc.log('Left click at', event.getLocationX(), event.getLocationY());
        } else if (event.getButton() === cc.EventMouse.BUTTON_RIGHT) {
            cc.log('Right click');
        }
    },
    onMouseScroll: (event: cc.EventMouse): void => {
        const scrollY = event.getScrollY();
        cc.log('Scroll delta:', scrollY);
    },
    onMouseMove: (event: cc.EventMouse): void => {
        const delta = event.getDelta();
        cc.log('Mouse moved by', delta.x, delta.y);
    }
}, this);
```

Button constants: `cc.EventMouse.BUTTON_LEFT` (0), `cc.EventMouse.BUTTON_RIGHT` (1), `cc.EventMouse.BUTTON_MIDDLE` (2).

Use `cc.eventManager.dispatchCustomEvent` to dispatch and `cc.eventManager.addCustomListener` to listen:

```typescript
// Listen for a custom event
const listener = cc.eventManager.addCustomListener('game:score_update', (event: cc.Event) => {
    const data = event.getUserData<{ score: number }>();
    cc.log('New score:', data.score);
});

// Dispatch the custom event with data
cc.eventManager.dispatchCustomEvent('game:score_update', { score: 100 });

// Remove when no longer needed
cc.eventManager.removeListener(listener);

// Or remove all listeners for that event name
cc.eventManager.removeCustomListeners('game:score_update');
```

Custom events are great for decoupled pub/sub communication between game systems (e.g., score updates, game state changes, UI notifications).

There are several ways to remove listeners:

```typescript
// 1. Remove a specific listener (keep a reference)
const listener = cc.eventManager.addListener({ ... }, node);
cc.eventManager.removeListener(listener);

// 2. Remove all listeners associated with a node
cc.eventManager.removeListeners(myNode);

// 3. Remove listeners from a node and all its children
cc.eventManager.removeListeners(myNode, true); // recursive

// 4. Remove all custom listeners by event name
cc.eventManager.removeCustomListeners('my:event');

// 5. Remove ALL listeners (use with caution)
cc.eventManager.removeAllListeners();
```

Best practice: store the listener reference and remove it in `onExit()`:

```typescript
class MyLayer extends cc.Layer {
    private _listener: cc.EventListener;
    onEnter() {
        super.onEnter();
        this._listener = cc.eventManager.addListener({ ... }, this);
    }
    onExit() {
        cc.eventManager.removeListener(this._listener);
        super.onExit();
    }
}
```

`cc.Touch` provides position and movement data for touch events:

```typescript
// World position (GL coordinates)
touch.getLocation(): cc.Point
touch.getLocationX(): number
touch.getLocationY(): number

// Previous frame's position
touch.getPreviousLocation(): cc.Point

// Where the touch first started
touch.getStartLocation(): cc.Point

// Movement delta since last event
touch.getDelta(): cc.Point

// Screen coordinates (before GL conversion)
touch.getLocationInView(): cc.Point
touch.getPreviousLocationInView(): cc.Point
touch.getStartLocationInView(): cc.Point

// Touch identifier (native only, undefined on H5)
touch.getID(): number | undefined
```

Example - dragging a node:
```typescript
onTouchMoved: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.EventTouch) => {
    const delta = touch.getDelta();
    node.x += delta.x;
    node.y += delta.y;
}
```

`cc.Event` is the base class for all events in the Cocos2d-x event system.

Key methods:
```typescript
event.getType(): number       // returns the event type constant
event.getUserData<T>(): T     // get custom data attached to event
event.setUserData(data: any): void  // set custom data
```

Type constants:
```typescript
cc.Event.TOUCH         // touch events
cc.Event.KEYBOARD      // keyboard events
cc.Event.ACCELERATION  // accelerometer events
cc.Event.MOUSE         // mouse events
cc.Event.CUSTOM        // custom user events
```

Example - checking event type:
```typescript
function handleEvent(event: cc.Event): void {
    switch (event.getType()) {
        case cc.Event.TOUCH:
            cc.log('Touch event received');
            break;
        case cc.Event.KEYBOARD:
            cc.log('Keyboard event received');
            break;
        case cc.Event.CUSTOM:
            const data = event.getUserData<{ message: string }>();
            cc.log('Custom event:', data.message);
            break;
    }
}
```

Here's a complete draggable sprite implementation using `TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE`:

```typescript
class DraggableSprite extends cc.Sprite {
    private _listener: cc.EventListener;

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        const self = this;

        this._listener = cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
            swallowTouches: true,
            onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): boolean => {
                const loc = touch.getLocation();
                const nodeSpace = self.convertToNodeSpace(loc);
                const size = self.getContentSize();
                const rect = cc.rect(0, 0, size.width, size.height);
                return cc.rectContainsPoint(rect, nodeSpace);
            },
            onTouchMoved: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.EventTouch): void => {
                const delta = touch.getDelta();
                self.x += delta.x;
                self.y += delta.y;
            },
            onTouchEnded: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): void => {
                cc.log('Dropped at', self.x, self.y);
            }
        }, this);
    }

    onExit(): void {
        cc.eventManager.removeListener(this._listener);
        super.onExit();
    }
}
```

The key is `onTouchBegan` returning `true` only when the touch is within the sprite's bounds, which claims the touch for this sprite.

Track pressed keys with a set and move the character each frame:

```typescript
class PlayerController extends cc.Layer {
    private _keysPressed: Set<number> = new Set();
    private _player: cc.Sprite;
    private _listener: cc.EventListener;
    private static readonly MOVE_SPEED = 200;

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        this._player = new cc.Sprite('res/player.png');
        this.addChild(this._player);

        this._listener = cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.KEYBOARD,
            onKeyPressed: (keyCode: cc.KEY, event: cc.Event): void => {
                this._keysPressed.add(keyCode);
            },
            onKeyReleased: (keyCode: cc.KEY, event: cc.Event): void => {
                this._keysPressed.delete(keyCode);
            }
        }, this);

        this.scheduleUpdate();
    }

    update(dt: number): void {
        const speed = PlayerController.MOVE_SPEED * dt;
        if (this._keysPressed.has(cc.KEY.w)) this._player.y += speed;
        if (this._keysPressed.has(cc.KEY.s)) this._player.y -= speed;
        if (this._keysPressed.has(cc.KEY.a)) this._player.x -= speed;
        if (this._keysPressed.has(cc.KEY.d)) this._player.x += speed;
    }

    onExit(): void {
        cc.eventManager.removeListener(this._listener);
        super.onExit();
    }
}
```

