output:
```typescript
class CustomButton extends cc.Sprite {
    private _listener: cc.EventListener;

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        this._listener = cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
            swallowTouches: true,
            onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): boolean => {
                const loc = this.convertToNodeSpace(touch.getLocation());
                const size = this.getContentSize();
                if (!cc.rectContainsPoint(cc.rect(0, 0, size.width, size.height), loc)) {
                    return false;
                }
                this.setScale(0.9);
                this.setOpacity(180);
                return true;
            },
            onTouchEnded: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): void => {
                this.setScale(1.0);
                this.setOpacity(255);
                this.onTapped();
            },
            onTouchCancelled: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): void => {
                this.setScale(1.0);
                this.setOpacity(255);
            }
        }, this);
    }

    private onTapped(): void {
        cc.log('Button tapped!');
    }

    onExit(): void {
        cc.eventManager.removeListener(this._listener);
        super.onExit();
    }
}
```

The hit test in `onTouchBegan` converts the world touch position to node-local space and checks if it falls within the sprite's content rectangle.

instruction:
Find the bug in this custom event code:

```typescript
class ScoreManager {
    private listener: cc.EventListener;

    init(): void {
        this.listener = cc.eventManager.addCustomListener('score:add', (event) => {
            const data = event.getUserData();
            this.addScore(data.points);
        });
    }

    addScore(points: number): void {
        cc.log('Added', points, 'points');
    }

    notifyScoreAdded(points: number): void {
        cc.eventManager.dispatchCustomEvent('score_add', { points: points });
    }
}
```

output:
There are two bugs:

**Bug 1: Event name mismatch.** The listener subscribes to `'score:add'` but `notifyScoreAdded` dispatches `'score_add'` (underscore instead of colon). The event will never be received.

**Bug 2: Missing type parameter on `getUserData`.** Without it, the return is untyped and will lack type safety.

Fixed code:
```typescript
class ScoreManager {
    private listener: cc.EventListener;
    private static readonly SCORE_EVENT = 'score:add';

    init(): void {
        this.listener = cc.eventManager.addCustomListener(
            ScoreManager.SCORE_EVENT,
            (event: cc.Event) => {
                const data = event.getUserData<{ points: number }>();
                this.addScore(data.points);
            }
        );
    }

    addScore(points: number): void {
        cc.log('Added', points, 'points');
    }

    notifyScoreAdded(points: number): void {
        cc.eventManager.dispatchCustomEvent(
            ScoreManager.SCORE_EVENT, // FIX: use same constant
            { points: points }
        );
    }

    destroy(): void {
        cc.eventManager.removeListener(this.listener);
    }
}
```

Extracting the event name into a constant prevents name mismatch bugs.

`cc.Touch.getDelta()` returns a `cc.Point` representing the movement delta (in GL world coordinates) since the last touch event.

```typescript
// Type signature
touch.getDelta(): cc.Point  // { x: number, y: number }
```

The `x` and `y` values represent how far the touch moved since the previous frame. This is commonly used for dragging and scrolling:

```typescript
// Drag a node to follow the finger
onTouchMoved: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.EventTouch): void => {
    const delta: cc.Point = touch.getDelta();
    myNode.x += delta.x;
    myNode.y += delta.y;
}

// Scroll a container
onTouchMoved: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.EventTouch): void => {
    const delta: cc.Point = touch.getDelta();
    scrollContainer.y += delta.y; // vertical scroll only
}
```

Note: `getDelta()` gives the same result as `cc.pSub(touch.getLocation(), touch.getPreviousLocation())`.

There are two priority systems:

**1. Scene graph priority** — pass a `cc.Node` as the second argument. Events are dispatched based on node z-order (higher z-order nodes receive events first).

```typescript
cc.eventManager.addListener({
    event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
    swallowTouches: true,
    onTouchBegan: (touch, event) => true
}, myNode); // priority determined by node's position in scene graph
```

**2. Fixed priority** — pass a number. Lower numbers execute first. Use `setPriority` to change it later.

```typescript
const listener = cc.eventManager.addListener({
    event: cc.EventListener.CUSTOM,
    callback: (event) => { /* ... */ }
}, 1); // fixed priority of 1

// Change priority later
cc.eventManager.setPriority(listener, -1); // now executes before priority 0+
```

Fixed priority listeners always execute before scene-graph priority listeners. When using `swallowTouches: true` with scene graph priority, higher z-order nodes swallow touches before lower ones see them.

Here's a basic vertical scroll view:

```typescript
class ScrollView extends cc.ClippingNode {
    private _content: cc.Node;
    private _listener: cc.EventListener;
    private _velocity: number = 0;
    private static readonly DECELERATION = 0.95;

    constructor(viewSize: cc.Size) {
        super();
        const stencil = new cc.DrawNode();
        stencil.drawRect(cc.p(0, 0), cc.p(viewSize.width, viewSize.height), cc.color(255, 255, 255), 0, cc.color(0, 0, 0));
        this.setStencil(stencil);
        this._content = new cc.Node();
        this.addChild(this._content);
    }

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        this._listener = cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
            swallowTouches: true,
            onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): boolean => {
                this._velocity = 0;
                return true;
            },
            onTouchMoved: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.EventTouch): void => {
                const delta = touch.getDelta();
                this._content.y += delta.y;
                this._velocity = delta.y;
            },
            onTouchEnded: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): void => {
                // velocity is preserved for inertia
            }
        }, this);
        this.scheduleUpdate();
    }

    update(dt: number): void {
        if (Math.abs(this._velocity) > 0.1) {
            this._content.y += this._velocity;
            this._velocity *= ScrollView.DECELERATION;
        } else {
            this._velocity = 0;
        }
    }

    addScrollContent(node: cc.Node): void {
        this._content.addChild(node);
    }

    onExit(): void {
        cc.eventManager.removeListener(this._listener);
        super.onExit();
    }
}
```

This uses inertia scrolling with deceleration. The `ClippingNode` masks content outside the view area.

